## The feature that quietly does all the real work: lifecycle policies

Here is the part that separates "we use S3" from "we designed S3 well."

You do not want to manually move millions of objects between classes.

That would be like personally walking every old file from your desk to the basement each night.
Technically possible. Spiritually terrible.

Lifecycle policies let you define rules such as:

- keep data in Standard for 30 days,
- move it to Standard-IA after 30 days,
- move it to Glacier Flexible Retrieval after 180 days,
- delete it after 5 years.

In other words, you tell S3 the story of how your data should age.

Example thought process:

- Hot when created
- Warm after a month
- Cold after six months
- Frozen for compliance after a year

That is where S3 becomes powerful.

Not when you upload objects.
When you let them age intentionally.

